Labs have unclear marking schemes and you seem to just lose marks without explanation. Overall, she's unhelpful and the course is more work than it needs to be.

She's pretty chill in this seminar course. Just do the readings and connect it to some random personal experience and that's usually enough to get an A. Definitely recommend taking this course to boost your GPA if you're good at spitting out essays and other "deep" reflections on readings.

"Innovative Teaching Methods in Chemistry" seminar. Utter garbage. The whole point of seminars is to encourage discussion, but if you say anything she remotely disagrees with, she'll just cut you off, and tell you to re-read the weird, dense articles she assigns. Class is brain-dead easy, just figure out what she thinks, and write that in an essay

She wants her students to fail. Tests are fair but often have mistakes. Marking schemes in the lab manual don't mean anything because she deducts marks for anything that she thinks should've been done. So you can get all the marks for a lab, but then get a 0 because of random deductions. Worst of the 16 profs I've had so far.

I was glad to have her before taking CHM247. She seems kinda nice in the seminar course. Any first year students looking to do a seminar course, do not take 'Innovative Teaching Methods in Chemistry' unless you are very interested in the subject. She's one of the rudest instructors that I have ever had in U of T. She will destroy your experience in U of T and she can also destroy your GPA in her tests if you don't work hard. If you want to ace her class, read the whole textbook before coming to her first class

Cecilia is an amazing prof. Her teaching style is not simply to give all the information we need to know, but to help us start to figure out how to think about problems.
